---
import MarketingLayout from "../layouts/MarketingLayout.astro";
---

<MarketingLayout
  title="MailAtlas: local email I/O for AI agents and data apps"
  description="MailAtlas: local email ingestion, export, sending, and audit trails for AI agents and data apps."
>
  <header class="topbar">
    <a class="brand" href="/">
      <span class="brand-mark"></span>
      <span>MailAtlas</span>
    </a>
    <nav class="topnav" aria-label="Primary">
      <a href="#overview">Overview</a>
      <a href="#inputs">Inputs</a>
      <a href="#fit">Fit</a>
      <a href="/docs/marketing/product-vision/">Vision</a>
      <a href="/docs/">Docs</a>
      <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/mailatlas">GitHub</a>
    </nav>
  </header>

  <main class="landing-main">
    <section class="hero" id="overview">
      <div class="hero-grid">
        <div class="hero-copy">
          <div class="eyebrow">Open-source local email I/O</div>
          <h1>MailAtlas: local email I/O for AI agents and data apps.</h1>
          <p class="lede">
            Read <code>.eml</code> files, import <code>mbox</code> mailbox files, or sync selected
            IMAP folders into one local store. MailAtlas keeps raw messages, cleaned text, HTML,
            inline images, file attachments, metadata, outbound snapshots, and send records together
            so the same email workspace can power AI, search, audits, and analytics.
          </p>
          <div class="hero-actions">
            <a class="button button-primary" href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/">Try file ingest</a>
            <a class="button button-secondary" href="/docs/getting-started/manual-imap-sync/">See IMAP sync</a>
          </div>
          <p class="hero-note">
            Start with files when your email is already on disk. Use <code>sync</code> when you
            need MailAtlas to connect to a live mailbox and fetch folders incrementally. Use
            <code>send</code> when your app needs outbound email through providers you configure.
          </p>
          <div class="hero-meta" aria-label="Core capabilities">
            <span>Open source</span>
            <span>No hosted service required</span>
            <span>Stores IMAP cursors, not mailbox credentials</span>
            <span>Sends without storing provider secrets</span>
            <span>Preserves inline images and attachments</span>
            <span>JSON, Markdown, HTML, PDF exports</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <aside class="hero-proof" aria-label="Product model">
          <div class="eyebrow">Choose an email path</div>
          <div class="mode-stack">
            <article class="mode-card">
              <span class="mode-card-accent">From files</span>
              <strong><code>ingest</code></strong>
              <p>Read <code>.eml</code> files or an <code>mbox</code> mailbox archive already on disk.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="mode-card">
              <span class="mode-card-accent">From live mailbox</span>
              <strong><code>sync</code></strong>
              <p>Fetch selected folders over IMAP into the same local store.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="mode-card">
              <span class="mode-card-accent">To configured providers</span>
              <strong><code>send</code></strong>
              <p>Render a local outbound record, then send through SMTP or Cloudflare Email Service.</p>
            </article>
          </div>
          <div class="flow-caption">Inbound paths create stored documents. Outbound paths create audit records.</div>
          <div class="record-card hero-record">
            <div class="code-header">stored document</div>
            <dl class="record-list">
              <div class="record-row">
                <dt>source_kind</dt>
                <dd><code>eml</code>, <code>mbox</code>, or <code>imap</code></dd>
              </div>
              <div class="record-row">
                <dt>raw_path</dt>
                <dd><code>raw/&lt;document-id&gt;.*</code></dd>
              </div>
              <div class="record-row">
                <dt>body_html_path</dt>
                <dd><code>html/&lt;document-id&gt;.html</code></dd>
              </div>
              <div class="record-row">
                <dt>assets</dt>
                <dd><code>assets/&lt;document-id&gt;/...</code> for inline images and attachments</dd>
              </div>
              <div class="record-row">
                <dt>exports</dt>
                <dd><code>json</code>, <code>markdown</code>, <code>html</code>, <code>pdf</code></dd>
              </div>
            </dl>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="proof-grid" id="inputs">
      <article class="proof-card">
        <span class="proof-label"><code>.eml</code></span>
        <strong>One message file on disk</strong>
        <p>Use this when you already have individual messages saved locally and want the fastest ingest path.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="proof-card">
        <span class="proof-label"><code>mbox</code></span>
        <strong>One mailbox file on disk</strong>
        <p>Use this when another system exported a mailbox file and you want to normalize every message inside it.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="proof-card">
        <span class="proof-label"><code>sync</code></span>
        <strong>Selected folders from a live mailbox</strong>
        <p>Use this when the messages still live in an inbox and you want MailAtlas to fetch them incrementally.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="proof-card">
        <span class="proof-label"><code>send</code></span>
        <strong>Outbound email through your provider</strong>
        <p>Use this when your application needs a local send record plus SMTP or Cloudflare delivery.</p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="content-grid" id="fit">
      <article class="panel">
        <div class="eyebrow">Use MailAtlas if</div>
        <h2>Your goal is local email I/O for software systems, not to replace an inbox client.</h2>
        <ul class="detail-list">
          <li>You need cleaned text plus links back to the raw email, HTML, inline images, and file attachments.</li>
          <li>You want local ingest and outbound audit trails for retrieval systems, analytics, or agent tooling.</li>
          <li>You want stable export formats such as JSON, Markdown, HTML, and PDF.</li>
          <li>You want to start with files, add manual IMAP sync later, and send through providers without storing secrets.</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="panel">
        <div class="eyebrow">Do not confuse it with</div>
        <h2>MailAtlas is a local email layer, not a hosted mailbox or deliverability product.</h2>
        <ul class="detail-list">
          <li>It is not background mailbox sync or a managed connector service.</li>
          <li>It is not hosted inbox search, inbox chat, a full mailbox client, or a deliverability service.</li>
          <li>It is not just a MIME decoder. It produces normalized outputs you can inspect, store, and pass to other systems.</li>
          <li>It is not trying to hide the source. Raw provenance stays attached to the stored document.</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="content-grid" id="install">
      <article class="panel">
        <div class="eyebrow">Start with files</div>
        <h2>The quickest proof is fixture-based ingest from disk.</h2>
        <p>
          Install the CLI, ingest the shipped fixtures, and inspect the stored records before
          pointing MailAtlas at your own email. This is the fastest way to verify the stored schema and
          export flow end to end.
        </p>
          <div class="code-block code-block-large">
            <div class="code-header">recommended path</div>
          <pre>python3.12 -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
python -m pip install mailatlas

export MAILATLAS_HOME="$PWD/.mailatlas"

mailatlas ingest \
  path/to/message.eml

mailatlas list</pre>
        </div>
        <ul class="detail-list detail-list-tight">
          <li>Use <code>python -m pip install "mailatlas[api]"</code> only if you want the published API extra.</li>
          <li>Use <code>uv tool install mailatlas</code> or Homebrew if you prefer a tool-style install.</li>
          <li>Clone the repo if you want the shipped fixtures or the demo API app.</li>
          <li>Use <code>sync</code> instead when the messages are still in a live mailbox.</li>
          <li>Export JSON, HTML, or Markdown anywhere with <code>--out</code>; PDF export is optional.</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="panel">
        <div class="eyebrow">What MailAtlas stores per message</div>
        <h2>One document, plus links back to raw email, attachments, and derived artifacts.</h2>
        <p>
          The default root is the built-in local storage layout. It keeps raw bytes, normalized HTML,
          extracted inline images and attachments, and SQLite metadata together so you can inspect
          them locally or move the data into your own services later.
        </p>
        <div class="workspace-grid">
          <div class="code-block code-block-large">
            <div class="code-header">reference root</div>
            <pre>.mailatlas/
  store.db
  raw/
  html/
  assets/
  exports/
  outbound/</pre>
          </div>
          <div class="record-card code-block-large">
            <div class="code-header">stored document</div>
            <dl class="record-list">
              <div class="record-row">
                <dt>subject</dt>
                <dd>Port dwell times normalize after weather disruptions</dd>
              </div>
              <div class="record-row">
                <dt>author</dt>
                <dd>Harbor Labs Charts &lt;charts@harborlabs.example&gt;</dd>
              </div>
              <div class="record-row">
                <dt>cleaning</dt>
                <dd><code>dropped_line_count: 0</code></dd>
              </div>
              <div class="record-row">
                <dt>html path</dt>
                <dd><code>html/&lt;document-id&gt;.html</code></dd>
              </div>
              <div class="record-row">
                <dt>asset refs</dt>
                <dd><code>assets/&lt;document-id&gt;/001-route-heatmap.svg</code> and any extracted attachments</dd>
              </div>
              <div class="record-row">
                <dt>exports</dt>
                <dd><code>--out ./document.json</code> or <code>exports/&lt;document-id&gt;.pdf</code></dd>
              </div>
            </dl>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="footer-cta">
      <div>
        <div class="eyebrow">Next steps</div>
        <h2>Choose files or a live mailbox and inspect the stored schema.</h2>
        <p>The docs are organized by task: installation, file quickstart, IMAP sync, CLI, Python, and schema.</p>
        <p class="hero-note">
          Questions, support, or private security reports:
          <a href="mailto:hello@mailatlas.dev"><code>hello@mailatlas.dev</code></a>
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="button button-primary" href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/">Open file quickstart</a>
        <a class="button button-secondary" href="/docs/getting-started/manual-imap-sync/">Open IMAP guide</a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</MarketingLayout>
